\headerbox{Abstract}{name=abstract,column=0}{
\vspace{0.02 \columnwidth}
\begin{center}
	\begin{minipage}{0.95\columnwidth}
		The Doppler shift of emission lines in the solar atmosphere is an important plasma diagnostic which allows for the determination of the bulk flow velocity of the material in the atmosphere. Measuring this quantity with high spatial, spectral and temporal resolution is important for initializing and verifying models of the solar atmosphere, but has proven to be a difficult observational problem. Using a computed tomography imaging spectrograph known as MOSES and an inversion algorithm utilizing convolutional neural networks, we develop a technique to recover the Doppler shift over a wide field-of-view with arcsecond resolution. We apply this technique to the data from the MOSES I flight.
	\end{minipage}
\end{center}
\vspace{0.00 \columnwidth}
}

\headerbox{\textit{MOSES} Instrument}{name=MOSES Instrument, column=0,below=abstract, above=bottom}{
\vspace{5pt}
\begin{center}
	\begin{minipage}{0.95\columnwidth}

		The slit employed by traditional spectrographs is important as it allows the spectrum of any given slice of the sun to be interpreted unambiguously. However, observing the Sun through a narrow slit can be prohibitive, as two-dimensional views of the Sun can only be acquired through the process of rastring, an operation that convolves together space and time. While rastering is adequate for 2D characterization of events with timescales much longer than the exposure time of the instrument, events on smaller timescales must be observed using a different method.
		
%		Removing the slit employed by a traditional spectrograph allows us to trade spectral bandwidth for spatial
		
		\hspace{8pt} The \textit{Multi-Order Solar EUV Spectrograph} (MOSES) is an instrument that recovers spectral information over a wide 2D field-of-view (FOV) by removing the slit employed by traditional spectrographs. This design choice convolves together spatial and spectral information onto an imaging sensor, trading spectral bandwidth for spatial bandwidth by using a narrow passband. Computational inversion algorithms are applied to images at multiple diffraction orders to separate the spatial/spectral information and recover plasma diagnostics over a large 2D area of the Sun.
		
		\begin{center}		
			\includegraphics[width=0.9\columnwidth]{Images/inversion}
			\captionof{figure}{Visualization describing how MOSES convolves spectral and spatial information together [1]. A dense object in $x-\lambda$ space appears to have relative shifts as imaged from different diffraction orders} 		  
		\end{center} 

	\end{minipage}
\end{center}
}   



